      },
      "source": [

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "YP5xNMHUKjp3"
      },
      "source": [
        "<u><h2>The data files</h2></u>\n",
        "<ul>\n",
        "  <li>The pulsar radio polarisation data is taken from the paper <a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018MNRAS.474.4629J/abstract\" target=\"_blank\"><i>Polarimetry of 600 pulsars from observations at 1.4 GHz with the Parkes radio telescope</i></a>.</li>\n",
        "  <li>The file may be downloaded from source through the DOI link: <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.25919/5c9af9fbe71c9\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.25919/5c9af9fbe71c9</a>.</li>\n",
        "  <li>Alternatively, download a copy from our <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EoD4wSfud6H4oeb_Y-TV3jI6Rd47yoK-/view?usp=sharing\n",
        "  \" target=\"_blank\">Google drive</a>.</li>\n",
        "  <li>Download and save a copy in your Google drive</li>\n",
        "</ul>\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "wq-X_5AdtRol"
      },
      "source": [
        "The data here is something like a Flexible Image Transport System (FITS).\r\n",
        "Although FITS format is extensively used for image\r\n",
        "data, the pulsar data here is not an image but follows the standard radio pulsar data\r\n",
        "storage format [PSRFITS](https://www.atnf.csiro.au/research/pulsar/psrfits_definition/Psrfits.html)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yvDx7n01PHHf"
      },
      "source": [
        "<h4>Access data from Google drive and load to notebook</h4>\n",
        "<p>The code in the cell below allows you to access a file saved in the Google drive. You need to simply do two things to make it work:</p>\n",
        "1. Enter the 'file_id'. This is an alpha-numeric string obtained from the sharing link of the data file. If the sharing link looks something like: <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EoD4wSfud6H4oeb_Y-TV3jI6Rd47yoK-/view?usp=sharing\"_blank\">https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EoD4wSfud6H4oeb_Y-TV3jI6Rd47yoK-/view?usp=sharing</a>, file_id is the part between \"d/\" and \"/view\".</br>\n",
        "2. Run the cell, click on the authentication link generated by the cell, sign-in with your Gmail account, copy the code generated in the next page, and enter it in the field provided below the cell to allow file access\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "b4hGCEqdzr16",
        "outputId": "d4fae821-96a3-4dd2-aee4-8e3a54b09143"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Import PyDrive and associated libraries.\n",
        "# This only needs to be done once per notebook.\n",
        "from pydrive.auth import GoogleAuth\n",
        "from pydrive.drive import GoogleDrive\n",
        "from google.colab import auth\n",
        "from oauth2client.client import GoogleCredentials\n",
        " \n",
        "# Authenticate and create the PyDrive client.\n",
        "# This only needs to be done once per notebook.\n",
        "auth.authenticate_user()\n",
        "gauth = GoogleAuth()\n",
        "gauth.credentials = GoogleCredentials.get_application_default()\n",
        "drive = GoogleDrive(gauth)\n",
        " \n",
        "# Download a file based on its file ID.\n",
        "# A file ID looks like: 1W7MZBYVQJTNDiZu1KE986ipQ0eobshg4\n",
        "file_id = '1W7MZBYVQJTNDiZu1KE986ipQ0eobshg4'\n",
        "downloaded = drive.CreateFile({'id': file_id})\n",
        "# print('Downloaded content \"{}\"'.format(downloaded.GetContentString()))\n",
        "print('title: %s, mimeType: %s' % (downloaded['title'], downloaded['mimeType']))"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "title: fitsfiles.tar.gz, mimeType: application/x-gzip\n"
          ],
          "name": "stdout"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6JcX9eFXQnR_"
      },
      "source": [
        "downloaded.GetContentFile('fitsfiles.tar.gz') # Downloads the file from the Google drive location"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },

        "<h3><b>Step 1.</b> Read the information stored in the FITS headers</h3>\n",

        "  <li> Print the header and data contained in PSRPARAM HDU. HDU names can be passed as index to the returned fits.open() object to access the HDU. HDU header is accessed through <i>.header</i> and data through <i>.data</i>.</li>\n",
        "  <li>Print the SUBINT HDU header and data which contains the IQUV data array. </li>\n",
        "<li>Print the DAT_OFFS and DAT_SCL values stored in the data section of the SUBINT HDU. </li>\n",

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Wt4kFE7tu_zV"
      },
      "source": [
        "Stokes parameters used to describe polarization Polarization of a\r\n",
        "monochromatic wave vector can be determined by determining (i) the electrical field\r\n",
        "amplitudes (E1,E2) along two orthogonal coordinates on the plane perpendicular to the\r\n",
        "direction of wave propagation and (ii) the relative phase-difference between them.\r\n",
        "\r\n",
        "In the most general case of arbitrary amplitude ratio and phase-di\u000berence between the\r\n",
        "two orthogonal components, the electric field vector traces an ellipse in the polarization\r\n",
        "plane and is said to be elliptically polarized. The polarization ellipse allows an alternate\r\n",
        "description of the polarization state using the field amplitudes (Ea and Eb) along the semimajor\r\n",
        "and semi-minor axes of the ellipse together with the inclination of the semi-major\r\n",
        "axis with respect to the original measurement axis.\r\n",
        "\r\n",
        "\r\n",
        "Using the parameters of the polarization ellipse,\r\n",
        "yet another, widely used, polarization state descriptors is given by the Stokes parameters\r\n",
        "and visualized using the Poincar\u0013e sphere. The Stokes parameters I; Q; U; V \r\n",
        "\r\n",
        "![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)"
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "<h3><b>Step 2.</b> Extract IQUV raw data values from the stored integer array</h3>\n",
        "<ul>\n",
        "<li>Obtain the raw IQUV data array by applying the scaling DAT_SCL and offset DAT_OFFS to the integer DATA array.</li>\n",
        "</ul>"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

        "id": "PsXB8Fn5LpXt",

      },
      "source": [
        "# Code for Step 2 goes here\r\n",

        "i= data[0]\r\n",

      "source": [
        "#Data Scale Factor\r\n",
        "dataSCL= subint.data['DAT_SCL']\r\n",

      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "array([[0.00107709, 0.0008538 , 0.00048415, 0.00066928]], dtype=float32)"

    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "iwFgMlRNq90z"
      },
      "source": [
        "def scaling(dataArr, dataSCL, dataOFF):\r\n",
        "    rawDATAi= (dataSCL[0,0]*dataArr[0]) + dataOFF[0,0]\r\n",
        "    rawDATAq= (dataSCL[0,1]*dataArr[1]) + dataOFF[0,1]\r\n",
        "    rawDATAu= (dataSCL[0,2]*dataArr[2]) + dataOFF[0,2]\r\n",
        "    rawDATAv= (dataSCL[0,3]*dataArr[3]) + dataOFF[0,3]\r\n",
        "    return rawDATAi, rawDATAq, rawDATAu, rawDATAv"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {

      "metadata": {
        "id": "4G6-XX-CLrXM"
      },
      "source": [
        "<h3><b>Step 3.</b> Isolate the I, Q, U, V components for the pulsar signal</h3>\n",
        "<ul>\n",
        "<li>Baseline subtraction for the I, Q, U, V components can be achieved by determining the average baseline value and subtracting.</li>\n",
        "<li>A simple way of detemining average baseline value, for most narrow radio profiles, is to sort the array and find the average for an appropriate sub-set of array values from the middle of the sorted array.</li>\n",
        "</ul>"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cUqT2bKtsrSk"
      },
      "source": [
        "#Different Channel Data Isolation\r\n",
        "DATAi, DATAq, DATAu, DATAv = scaling(data, dataSCL, dataOFF)"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "vWvk3NChs48q"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Function to determine baseline average of a I, Q, U, or V array\r\n",
        "def baselineSUB(unscaledData):\r\n",
        "    sortedData= np.sort(unscaledData)\r\n",
        "    baselineData= sortedData[0,300:612]\r\n",
        "    return unscaledData-np.mean(baselineData)"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "lA57XTwzgp7D"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Code to convert raw IQUV data to IQUV data of the pulsar\r\n",
        "DATAiCorrected= baselineSUB(DATAi)\r\n",
        "DATAqCorrected= baselineSUB(DATAq)\r\n",
        "DATAuCorrected= baselineSUB(DATAu)\r\n",
        "DATAvCorrected= baselineSUB(DATAv)"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "B5kik2r5NuUj"
      },
      "source": [
        "<h3><b>Step 4.</b> Calculate the linear polarization component and the polarization angle</h3>\n",
        "<ul>\n",
        "<li>Intensity of linear polarization component is obtained from $$L = \\sqrt{Q^2+U^2}$$</li>\n",
        "<li>Polarization angle is obtained by using the expression $$\\psi = \\frac{1}{2}\\arctan\\left(\\frac{U}{Q}\\right)$$</li>\n",
        "</ul>"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "rbsULuZBPKlr"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Code for Step 4\n",
        "polAngle= np.degrees(0.5* np.arctan((DATAuCorrected/DATAqCorrected)))"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "XZRaj8HlfqgA",
        "outputId": "796a4de5-ef66-4404-b3be-623bc6c28d3e"
      },
      "source": [
        "polAngle.max(), polAngle.min()"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "(44.698753, -44.88928)"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {
            "tags": []
          },
          "execution_count": 27
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Rx20fdbkfz96"
      },
      "source": [
        "linearPol= np.sqrt(np.square(DATAqCorrected)+np.square(DATAuCorrected))"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
